<entry>
<author><name><![CDATA[MottZilla]]></name></author>
<updated>2012-05-10T21:18:09-07:00</updated>
<published>2012-05-10T21:18:09-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8873&amp;p=93654#p93654</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8873&amp;p=93654#p93654"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Major Famicom Disk System security breach]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=8873&amp;p=93654#p93654"><![CDATA[
Besides ROM memory falling in price dramatically and battery backed RAM on carts, another key problem with the FDS was Nintendo's strict licensing. If I recall, Nintendo got a partial copyright for any FDS games released. The profit margins may have been lower, etc. From a business perspective for developers it was a bad deal. <br /><br />So it was both business and the aging FDS versus the better cheaper technology for carts. The FDS could have been upgraded with a new RAZM adapter, but that wouldn't have solved the piracy or loading issues. Later NES games were very commonly 128K, 256K, and 512K. FDS disks hold around 128K using both sides and I think it takes over a minute to scan the whole disk. So it would take considerable time before getting to play later games if you went that route.<br /><br />And ROM was probably cheaper than a large initial investment in DRAM for a disk type system for later games.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=1726">MottZilla</a> — Thu May 10, 2012 9:18 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
